5-8. The image in this place is not clear. We may perhaps compare 2. 18. 29. In both cases Horace is pointing the irony of fate, which allows a man to begin to build what he may not live to finish. In both cases ‘Orcus' or ‘Necessitas' are represented under images borrowed from the employnnent of the rich man himself. In a. 18 he is busy planning his palare. Death has his measuring rod too, andis planning a home for him which he shall yet more surely tenant. Here he is laying the foundations of his palace deep in the sea; but who knows that Fate may not snatch his hammer from him and ‘drive the last nails into the gahle-top’ herself? He will have the toll, but he will not finish the work himself. Death will stop him.
